@flexiarg coordination/ARGUMENT
@title Coordination Argument (Gate Pipeline)
@audience futon maintainers, coordination reviewers
@tone formal-analytic
@keywords coordination, gate, proof-path, typed-graph, evidence
@references [coordination/task-shape-validation coordination/mandatory-psr coordination/mandatory-pur coordination/session-durability-check futon-theory/theory-as-exotype]

! conclusion:
  A six-gate pipeline over typed evidence records is the minimal structure that turns messy activity into organized knowledge with auditable records.

  + context:
    Futon3 already has working pieces (transport, check DSL, trails, workday intake, pattern retrieval bridges), but they are not composed into a single boundary that enforces pattern use and durable evidence.

  + IF:
    you want FUTON3 to reliably produce records that other futons can use to learn and act

  + HOWEVER:
    when pattern selection, execution, validation, and persistence are scattered, the system cannot enforce invariants like "no work runs without PSR" or "no success acknowledged before durability"

  + THEN:
    compose the existing implementations through a gate pipeline:
    - G5 defines TaskSpec and binds intent to mission + success criteria
    - G4 authorizes an agent and records an Assignment
    - G3 requires PSR (or gap declaration) and records candidates
    - G2 runs bounded execution and registers an Artifact
    - G1 produces PUR by evaluating criteria against artifacts
    - G0 gates success on durability and requires PAR to close the loop

  + BECAUSE:
    this structure is checkable (gate ordering, typed rejections, evidence shapes) and creates a proof-path that can be replayed, audited, and fed into glacial library evolution

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Define a machine-checkable exotype diagram and concrete instantiation, and stop-the-line when concrete ports/edges drift from the exotype.]
    next[Wire futon3b gate modules to futon3 transport surfaces (WS/HTTP) while preserving the "first failing gate wins" invariant.]

